The paper discusses a mechanistic model for citation dynamics of individual papers, which is relevant to the fields of information retrieval (cs.IR) and digital libraries (cs.DL). The paper also discusses the universal temporal pattern of citation histories, which is relevant to the field of social and information networks (cs.SI). Additionally, the potential policy implications of reliable measures of influence may be relevant to the field of cybernetics (cs.CY) and cryptography (cs.CR).
